This book, which evolved from classroom notes developed for three microprocessor 
courses taught at California State Poly University, presents the fundamental 
concepts of assembly language programming and system design for typical 
microprocessors, such as the Motorola MC 68000/MC 68020 and Intel Pentium. This 
self-contained book includes a number of basic topics and assumes a basic 
digital logic background. The author has chosen to emphasize the characteristics 
and principles common to typical microprocessors. He demonstrates the basic 
microcomputer interfacing techniques via examples using the simplest possible 
devices such as switches, LEDs, A/D converters, hexadecimal keyboard, and seven
-segment displays.

